29 (5) SHORELINE RESTORATION. The deposition of dredged
30 material or natural or artificial material directly on or
31 adjacent to an existing shoreline to restore or preserve the
32 shoreline and the deposition of such material south of Dauphin
33 Island or south of the Fort Morgan Peninsula for the
34 restoration of Dauphin Island or Sand Island. This term
35 includes a living shoreline project.
36 (b) This section shall apply only in coastal areas.
37 (c) Any person that dredges more than one million cubic
38 yards of material in a year shall cause at least 70 percent of
39 the dredged material to be beneficially used. No funds
40 appropriated from the State General Fund to a person shall be
41 used for expenses incurred by the person to comply with the
42 requirements of this section.
43 (d) The Alabama Department of Environmental Management
44 and the Alabama Department of Conservation and Natural
45 Resources shall adopt rules to implement this section,
46 including revising the Alabama Coastal Area Management Program
47 as necessary.
48 (e) A person shall not be required to comply with
49 subsection (c):
50 (1) Except to the extent that federal funds are
51 available and have been allocated for beneficial use when
52 permitted and approved beneficial use sites are available in
53 the state and have a demonstrated capacity for suitable
54 material; or
55 (2) If the Governor, by order or proclamation declaring
56 a state of emergency, specifically references this section and
